{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"080447be-b320-451b-9ea2-75d0fb936b5c","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on Kubernetes:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```powershell\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace`\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n$env:PATH += \";C:\\Users\\ContainerUser\\.dotnet\\tools\"\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect a CPU trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file. Copy it out with:\n```sh\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### 5. Analyze\nOpen the `.nettrace` in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub), **PerfView** (convert with `dotnet-trace convert --format speedscope`), or [speedscope.app](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool install` fails due to no SDK in the container, you can download the standalone `dotnet-trace` from the [.NET diagnostics releases](https://github.com/dotnet/diagnostics) or use `perfcollect` / `PerfView` from the host.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"76690a8f-0c2f-4738-83d7-f739559218dc","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":425,"requestId":"67C9:1EA4:4E611F4:558D3E7:69FD3AEF"},"id":"e7def800-3834-4087-8d90-27397bc1ec40","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:23:05.048Z","parentId":"bf8c1e89-e3f8-40b6-bc7a-d0e5dea1e358"}
